Just like in the title.
When you call Body.getWorldPoint several times it will always return reference to the same object

Vector2 vec1 = body.getWorldPoint(new Vector2 (0,0));
Vector2 vec2 = body.getWorldPoint(new Vector2 (500,500));

this code will cause vec1 and vec2 having the value of (500,500).
It's easy to get around it by Vector2(Vector2 v) constructor, but it is still confusing.

JsonValue#asBoolean:

``` java
public boolean asBoolean () {
        switch (type) {
        case stringValue:
            return stringValue.equalsIgnoreCase("true");
        case doubleValue:
            return doubleValue == 0;
        case longValue:
            return longValue == 0;
        case booleanValue:
            return longValue != 0;
        }
        throw new IllegalStateException("Value cannot be converted to boolean: " + type);
    }
```

It looks like the returns for case doubleValue and longValue were meant to be `!= 0`, not `== 0`.

I encountered this in my game prototype, so I created a new LibGDX project to test it. It happens sporadically, but I couldn't reproduce it until adding a frame buffer to the game. That could be a coincidence though, because I cannot reliably reproduce the issue.

It's maddening that this happens sporadically, but the best way I've found to reproduce it is to open the game, turn off the phone, and reopen the game about three hours later. When I do this, the blank clear color screen shows up about 30% of the time. I have been doing this with my personal phone, so its possible that my occasional use of the Chrome browser is contributing to whatever RAM or GPU condition triggers it.

However, I once encountered the issue by opening the game, hitting the power button, hitting the power button again to turn on the screen, and unlocking the lock screen. The game returned to the clear color screen. However, since then I have tried turning the screen on and off many times and couldn't get this to happen again.

There are no black rectangles where the textures were, so I don't think the problem is them getting disposed. I am also setting the projection matrix to identity on each frame, so I don't think the resize method is confounding this.

I set it to show a different color for the clear color depending on phone orientation. Rotating the screen changes the clear color back and forth, but the textures do not reappear.

I realize you might not be able to make progress on this without being able to reproduce it. If so, I would appreciate some tips on how I might get started tracking it down. Maybe someone has some idea what could cause meshes not to draw at all, while the clear color still shows. Could some of the gl settings be getting changed somehow, like face culling turned on? I'm not familiar with the iOS backend.

Gradle version: 2.1
Robovm plugin version 0.0.10
Robovm version 0.0.14
Gdx version 1.3.1
Device: iPhone 5
iOS version: 7.1.2
Using Android Studio

I updated the above in the various Gradle files. You can copy and paste the bottom into the MyGdxGame in a new project:

``` java
public class MyGdxGame extends ApplicationAdapter {
    SpriteBatch batch;
    Texture img;
    FrameBuffer frameBuffer;

    final Matrix4 matrix4 = new Matrix4();
    int screenWidth;
    int screenHeight;
    float doubleInitialWidth, doubleInitialHeight;

    @Override
    public void create () {
        batch = new SpriteBatch();
        img = new Texture("badlogic.jpg");
        doubleInitialWidth = Gdx.graphics.getWidth()*2;
        doubleInitialHeight = Gdx.graphics.getHeight()*2;
    }

    @Override
    public void resize (int width, int height){
        screenWidth = width;
        screenHeight = height;

        if (frameBuffer!=null)
            frameBuffer.dispose();
        frameBuffer = new FrameBuffer(Pixmap.Format.RGBA4444, width, height, false);
    }

    @Override
    public void render () {
        Gdx.gl.glClearColor(screenWidth/ doubleInitialWidth, screenHeight/ doubleInitialHeight, (screenWidth<=0 || screenHeight<=0)? 0.5f : 1, 1);
        Gdx.gl.glClear(GL20.GL_COLOR_BUFFER_BIT);

        frameBuffer.begin();
        Gdx.gl.glClearColor(0, 0, 1, 1);
        Gdx.gl.glClear(GL20.GL_COLOR_BUFFER_BIT);
        matrix4.setToOrtho2D(0, 0, screenWidth, screenHeight);
        batch.setProjectionMatrix(matrix4);
        batch.begin();
        batch.draw(img, 0, 0);
        batch.end();
        frameBuffer.end();

        matrix4.idt();
        batch.setProjectionMatrix(matrix4);
        batch.begin();
        batch.draw(frameBuffer.getColorBufferTexture(), -.8f, .8f, 1.6f, -1.6f);

        matrix4.setToOrtho2D(0, 0, screenWidth, screenHeight);
        batch.setProjectionMatrix(matrix4);
        batch.draw(img, screenWidth-img.getWidth(), 0);
        batch.end();
    }

    @Override
    public void dispose(){
        batch.dispose();
        img.dispose();
    }

}
```

I might be encountering the issue mentioned here: https://github.com/libgdx/libgdx/issues/1794

However, I can confirm that if I change the clear color, the screen shows the clear color.
